<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_TrafoLineSegment"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>


	  <title>Example: Transformation of a Line Segment</title>
	  <caption>Transformation of a Line Segment</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>In the picture below the line segment <math>
                  <latex>[a,b]</latex>
               </math> on the left gets transformed into the red curve on the right.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
            <img src="ims/Trafo_LineSegment.png"/>
         </media>
			
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>To fit this intuitive process into the mathematical formalism of functions, we do the following:</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <ul>
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>We take the interval <math>
                        <latex>[a,b]</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> as the domain of the transforming function <math>
                        <latex>f</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The plane <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> on the right is the target of <math>
                        <latex>f</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The curve on the right is the transformed line segment. This is also called the image of <math>
                        <latex>f</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
			      </ul>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>The function <math>
                  <latex>f\from [a,b]\to \RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> transforms <math>
                  <latex>[a,b]</latex>
               </math> into the curve on the right. Note that the image of <math>
                  <latex>f</latex>
               </math> need not be equal to the target <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math>. Note also that the end point <math>
                  <latex>a</latex>
               </math> of <math>
                  <latex>[a,b]</latex>
               </math> gets transformed into the end point <math>
                  <latex>f(a)</latex>
               </math> of the curve on the right, and that the end point <math>
                  <latex>b</latex>
               </math> of <math>
                  <latex>[a,b]</latex>
               </math> gets transformed into the end point <math>
                  <latex>f(b)</latex>
               </math> of the curve.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
	  </showme>	
</showme.pack>
